<Layout title="Nutritional & Skin Integrity Assessment Tools" description="Nutritional and skin integrity assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Nutritional &amp; Skin Integrity</div>
  <h1>Nutritional &amp; Skin Integrity Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Tools for identifying malnutrition risk, pressure injury risk, and nutritional status across patient populations.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Braden Scale</strong> — Six-subscale pressure injury risk assessment: Sensory Perception, Moisture, Activity, Mobility, Nutrition, Friction/Shear. Score 6–23; ≤18 = at risk; ≤9 = very high risk.</li>
      <li><strong>Braden Q Scale</strong> — Pediatric adaptation of the Braden Scale with seven subscales including tissue perfusion and oxygenation. Validated for children under 5 years.</li>
      <li><strong>Norton Scale</strong> — Five-item pressure injury risk scale: Physical condition, Mental condition, Activity, Mobility, Incontinence. Score 5–20; ≤14 = risk for pressure injury.</li>
      <li><strong>Waterlow Scale</strong> — Comprehensive pressure ulcer risk tool assessing weight/height, skin type, sex/age, special risks, continence, mobility, appetite, and neurological deficit.</li>
      <li><strong>PUSH Tool (Pressure Ulcer Scale for Healing)</strong> — Tracks wound healing progress by measuring wound surface area, exudate amount, and tissue type; total score 0–17.</li>
      <li><strong>MNA (Mini Nutritional Assessment)</strong> — 18-item nutritional screen validated for older adults; full version and short form available. Score &lt;17 = malnourished; 17–23.5 = at risk.</li>
      <li><strong>MUST (Malnutrition Universal Screening Tool)</strong> — Three-step nutritional risk tool: BMI, unintentional weight loss, and acute disease effect. Guides intervention intensity.</li>
      <li><strong>NRS-2002 (Nutritional Risk Screening)</strong> — Hospital nutritional risk screening using BMI, weight loss, food intake, and disease severity. Score ≥3 indicates nutritional risk requiring intervention.</li>
      <li><strong>SGA (Subjective Global Assessment)</strong> — Clinician-rated nutritional status tool: history (weight change, dietary intake, GI symptoms, functional capacity) and physical examination.</li>
      <li><strong>STAMP (Screening Tool for the Assessment of Malnutrition in Paediatrics)</strong> — Pediatric nutritional risk screen using diagnosis, nutritional intake, and weight/height measurements.</li>
      <li><strong>Weight-for-Height Z-Score</strong> — Pediatric nutritional status indicator; Z-score &lt;−2 indicates wasting; &lt;−3 indicates severe acute malnutrition per WHO standards.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
